         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>Blocks and parts of blocks each originally 2.06 wide. The blocks clearly come from the opening of a text in honour of an emperor:
               cf. The formula
               <foreign xml:lang="grc">ὑπὲρ Αὐτοκρατορος Καισαρος <gap reason="ellipsis"/> νεικας και σωτηρίας καὶ αἰωνιου διαμονας καὶ τοῦ πάντος αὐτοῦ οἰκοῦ</foreign>. </p>
            <p>Of the emperor's name there survives only <foreign xml:lang="grc">ΝΕΡ</foreign> and while
               <foreign xml:lang="grc">Νέρων</foreign> is possible, the letter forms suggest a second century date and therefore
               <foreign xml:lang="grc">Νέρουα</foreign>, probably from the filiation. If the stoa is the main gymnasium, 
               whose dilapidated state is mentioned by Hadrian <!-- check -->, the earliest emperor likely is Antoninus Pius.</p>
         </div>
         
